available: uhttps://muse.jhu.edu/book/143015/02986cam a22005054a musev2_147385MdBmJHUP20260630050239.0m     o  d        cr||||||||nn|n251017s2025    sz      o      00 0 eng d  a9783906927695  z9783906927688  a(OCoLC)1601191732  aMdBmJHUPcMdBmJHUP1 aMelber, Henning,d1950-4aut14aThe Windhoek Old Location History and Photographs / cHenning Melber, Dieter Hinrichs ; with contributions by Bience Gawanas and Ewald Uazuvara Kapombo Katjivena 1aBasel :bBasler Afrika Bibliographien,c2025 3aBaltimore, Md. :bProject MUSE, c0000 4c&copy;2025  a1 online resource: billustrations, colour maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAt head of title: A symbol of a people's determination  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 115-118)0 aOpen AccessfUnrestricted online access2star8 aThe story of Windhoek's Old Location is one of African replacement and at the same time of creating home against all odds under the enforced, restricted living conditions of Apartheid. Being adjacent to the White centre of town, urban planning replaced the Old Location with the newly established township Katutura in the late 1950s. Many residents refused to be re-located. Escalating protest resulted in deadly clashes on 10th December 1959 when the colonial police opened fire on unarmed residents. At least 13 were killed and more than 40 recorded as wounded. After years of forced removal, the Old Location was officially closed in 1968.?This book contributes to a commemorative culture of a crucial place and space during a formative time in Namibia's history. It offers a partial reconstruction of a social history of the Old Location. Personal memories of former residents, as far as they are accessible, contrast the colonial archives.?The captivating photographs by the German photographer Dieter Hinrichs, who documented social events and everyday life in the Location between 1959 and 1960, are essential. Many are published here for the first time. They speak louder than words  aPrint version  aDescription based on print version record. 4aResettlement 4aPhotographs 4aApartheid 4aSocial conditions 4aUrban areas 4aNamibiazWindhoek  aTownship 7aElectronic books. 2local1 aKatjivena, Uazuvara Ewald Kapombo4aft1 aGawanas, Bience4aui1 aDieter, Hinrichs4ill0 aSymbol of a people's determination2 aProject Muse.edistributor 0aBook collections on Project MUSE.40zFull text available: uhttps://muse.jhu.edu/book/147385/03797cam a22006254a musev2_148002MdBmJHUP20260630050245.0m     o  d        cr||||||||nn|n230119s2023    enk     o      00 0 eng d  a9781529225648  z9781529225631  z9781529225624  a(OCoLC)1357136998  aMdBmJHUPcMdBmJHUP 4aHT1510 a307.76223/eng/202306011https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/ddc/E44hgkBQMb4rydfjJfdVMdCJrm00aInfrastructuring Urban Futures : bThe Politics of Remaking Cities / cedited by Alan Wiig, Kevin Ward, Theresa Enright, Mike Hodson, Hamil Pearsall and Jonathan Silver. 1aBristol, UK  :bBristol University Press,c2023. 3aBaltimore, Md. :bProject MUSE, c0000 4c&copy;2023.  a1 online resource (230 pages): bcolor illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.00tFront Matter --tContents --tList of Figures and Tables --tNotes on Contributors --tAcknowledgements --tIntroduction --tInfrastructure and the Tragedy of Development --tTemporalities of the Climate Crisis: Maintenance, Green Finance and Racialized Austerity in New York City and Cape Town --tEmerging Techno-ecologies of Energy: Examining Digital Interventions and Engagements with Urban Infrastructure --tInfrastructural Reparations: Reimagining Reparative Justice in Haiti and Puerto Rico --tMaking Shit Social: Combined Sewer Overflows, Water Citizenship and the Infrastructural Commons --tMore than 'Where You Do Football': Reconceptualizing London's Urban Green Spaces through Green Infrastructure Planning --tGlobal Infrastructure and Urban Futures: London's Transforming Royal Albert Dock --tOn Fetishes, Fragments and Futures: Regionalizing Infrastructural Lives --tIncomplete Futures of Urban Infrastructure --tIndex0 aOpen AccessfUnrestricted online access2star  aFocusing on material and social forms of infrastructure, this edited collection draws on rich empirical details from cities across the global North and South. The book asks the reader to think through the different ways in which infrastructure comes to be present in cities and its co-constitutive relationships with urban inhabitants and wider processes of urbanisation. Considering the climate emergency, economic transformation, public health crises, and racialized inequality, the book argues that paying attention to infrastructures' past, present and future allows us to understand and respond to the current urban condition.  aDescription based on print version record. 7aSociology, Urban2fast 7aInfrastructure (Economics)2fast 7aCity planning2fast 7aCities and towns2fast 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh 7aurban sociology.2aat 7acities.2aat 6aSociologie urbaine. 6aVilles. 0aInfrastructure (Economics) 0aSociology, Urban. 0aCity planning. 0aCities and towns. 7aElectronic books. 2local1 aSilver, Jonathan,eeditor.1 aPearsall, Hamil,eeditor.1 aHodson, Mike,eeditor.1 aEnright, Theresa,eeditor.1 aWard, Kevin,eeditor.1 aWiig, Alan,eeditor.18iPrint version:z97815292256242 aProject Muse.edistributor 0aBook collections on Project MUSE.40zFull text available: uhttps://muse.jhu.edu/book/148002/03597cam a22005894a musev2_148087MdBmJHUP20260701050331.0m     o  d        cr||||||||nn|n260128t20262026miu     o      00 0 eng d  a9780472905881  z9780472058105  z9780472078103  a(OCoLC)1570336700  aMdBmJHUPcMdBmJHUP 4aHQ12191 aMbure, Wanjirũ G.,eauthor1https://orcid.org/0009-0006-8457-30261https://ror.org/03hsf057310aOut for Glamour in Africa : bA History of Black Urban Femininities in Drum Magazine / cWanjirũ G Mbure. 1aAnn Arbor :bUniversity of Michigan Press,c2026. 3aBaltimore, Md. :bProject MUSE, c0000 4c&copy;2026.  a1 online resource: billustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier0 aAfrican Perspectives Series  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 239-249) and index.0 aOpen AccessfUnrestricted online access2star  aRenegotiating Black femininities through Drum magazine. Out for Glamour in Africa critically reflects on how Black women utilized Drum magazine, a leading publication in Africa during the era of independence, for political empowerment and constructing notions of Black femininity. Wanjirũ G. Mbure terms the concept of femme urbAfricana, a model of Black femininity depicted as urban, political, fashionable, paradoxically Afrocentric, heteronormative, and transnational. Foregrounding stories of the women who embodied these traits and the social, political, and economic forces that shaped their presence in Drum, Mbure argues that these representations of Black women from Africa, the Caribbean, Europe, and the United States produced a novel form of Black urban femininity.  Utilizing a breadth of archival materials from cover girl photographs, advertisements, and columns, to readers' comments, Mbure reveals the complex relationship between the Black urban woman and the era's contested ideals within a transnational matrix.1 fThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-Non-Commercial 4.0 International Licenseuhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aDescription based on print version record. 6aFemmes en milieu urbainxAspect socialy20e siecle. 6aFemmes en milieu urbainxAspect psychologiquey20e siecle. 6aToilettey20e siecle. 6aFeminitey20e siecle. 6aFemmes noiresxAspect socialy20e siecle. 6aFemmes noiresxAspect psychologiquey20e siecle. 0aUrban womenxSocial aspectsy20th century. 0aUrban womenxPsychological aspectsy20th century. 0aBeauty, Personaly20th century. 0aFemininityy20th century. 0aWomen, BlackxSocial aspectsy20th century. 0aWomen, BlackxPsychological aspectsy20th century.00aDrum (Johannesburg, South Africa) 7aElectronic books. 2local2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan),epublisher.18cOriginalz047205810Xz9780472058105z0472078100z9780472078103w(OCoLC)15384661802 aProject Muse.edistributor 0aAfrican perspectives (University of Michigan. Press) 0aBook collections on Project MUSE.40zFull text available: uhttps://muse.jhu.edu/book/148087/01440cam a22003854a musev2_141376MdBmJHUP20260702050058.0m     o  d        cr||||||||nn|n260414s2026    xx      o      00 0 eng d  a9781626711709  z9781626711686  z9781626711693  z9781626711679  a(OCoLC)1585319601  aMdBmJHUPcMdBmJHUP1 aPetrungaro, Stefano.10aWorking at the Margins in Interwar Yugoslavia 1bPurdue University Pressc2026 3aBaltimore, Md. :bProject MUSE, c0000 4c&copy;2026  a1 online resource (304 pages).  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier0 aCentral European Studies0 aOpen AccessfUnrestricted online access2star  aProstitutes, beggars, folk healers, peddlers, wandering artists, and bear-leaders: Working at the Margins in Interwar Yugoslavia shows how work shaped their relations with the state and the rest of their world.8 aAccessibility summary: N/A  aDescription based on print version record. 7aElectronic books. 2local2 aProject Muse.edistributor 0aBook collections on Project MUSE.40zFull text available: uhttps://muse.jhu.edu/book/141376/01782cam a22004094a musev2_141382MdBmJHUP20260702050101.0m     o  d        cr||||||||nn|n260321s2026    inu     o      00 0 spa d  a9781626712454 