t Muse.edistributor 0aBook collections on Project MUSE.40zFull text available: uhttps://muse.jhu.edu/book/148142/03507cam a22005294a musev2_143085MdBmJHUP20260708050813.0m     o  d        cr||||||||nn|n251209s2026    onc     o      00 0 eng d  a9781487564049  z9781487564032  z9781049804224  z9781049804231  a(OCoLC)1559874175  aMdBmJHUPcMdBmJHUP  ae-sw---0 a305.4209487/3qCaOONL223/eng/202512091 aNorsted, Kristian Sandbekk,eauthor.10aAnxious Intersectionality : bAn Anthropology of Swedish Feminist Activism / cKristian Sandbekk Norsted. 1aLondon :bUniversity of Toronto Press,c2026. 3aBaltimore, Md. :bProject MUSE, c0000 4c&copy;2026.  a1 online resource (192 pages).  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.0 aOpen AccessfUnrestricted online access2star  a"Anxious Intersectionality offers an ethnographic exploration of feminist activism in Stockholm, Scandinavia’s largest city and a vibrant hub for feminist organizing in the late 2010s. Drawing on thirteen months of immersive fieldwork across a diverse range of activist spaces – including a queer feminist safe-space vegan café, Sweden’s feminist political party and its youth wing, an organization for male feminists and allies, a women and non-binary separatist fanzine group, feminist markets, protests, and social media – the book examines the pervasive anxiety that shapes feminist activism today. Rather than treating anxiety as a personal or psychological issue, the book elaborates on how it is collectively produced and practiced within an activist community through the concept of interpretive precedence. Confronting the sources and drivers of internal conflict and anxiety in activist spaces, researcher Kristian Sandbekk Norsted highlights how movements risk becoming pacified and fragmented. Offering a rare look into the world of activist communities, Norsted explores intersectionality beyond the bounds of theory. The book offers a critical yet empathetic account of underlying tensions within activist groups, contributing to broader debates on feminism, activism, intersectionality, and the emotional politics of social movements."--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on print version record. 6aFeminisme et anthropologiezSuedezStockholm. 6aIntersectionnalitezSuedezStockholm. 6aMouvements sociauxzSuedezStockholm. 6aFeminismezSuedezStockholm. 0aFeminist anthropologyzSwedenzStockholm. 0aIntersectionality (Sociology)zSwedenzStockholm. 0aAnxietyxSocial aspectszSwedenzStockholm. 0aSocial movementszSwedenzStockholm. 0aActivismzSwedenzStockholm. 0aFeminismzSwedenzStockholm. 7aElectronic books. 2local18iPrint version:aNorsted, Kristian Sandbekk.tAnxious intersectionality.dToronto ; Buffalo ; London : University of Toronto Press, 2026z1487564031z9781487564032w(OCoLC)15597843052 aProject Muse.edistributor 0aBook collections on Project MUSE.40zFull text available: uhttps://muse.jhu.edu/book/143085/03594cam a22006494a musev2_147861MdBmJHUP20260709050849.0m     o  d        cr||||||||nn|n241213s1985    nyu     o      00 0 eng d  a9798888661789  z9780883442203  a(OCoLC)1602841261  aMdBmJHUPcMdBmJHUP1 aenghspa 4aBT303.2b.S4413 19850 a232.9/082191https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/ddc/E38P8MTBYmc6jhVbBJ3QPwVdJX1 aSegundo, Juan Luis.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PBJfmvfWcdwTp7yD9bBxMT310aHistoria y actualidad--Sinópticos y Pablo.nPart 1.lEnglish14aThe Historical Jesus of the Synoptics / cJuan Luis Segundo ; translated from the Spanish by John Drury. 1aMaryknoll, NY :bOrbis Books,c1985. 3aBaltimore, Md. :bProject MUSE, c0000 4c&copy;1985.  a1 online resource.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier0 aJesus of Nazareth, yesterday and today ;vv. 2  aTranslation of: Historia y 